ubstack.com/redirect/995e0b1d-956c-45c5-90e3-f0de793b9573?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ=
3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
If you feel as motivated as I do after reading about Varda, now might be th=
e perfect time to go get in the best shape of your life and start doing big=
 things. Create [ https://substack.com/redirect/995e0b1d-956c-45c5-90e3-f0d=
e793b9573?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNp=
U ] can help. Dan set out to reverse the creatine stigma, and in just a few=
 months, thousands of people are using it and confirming what he knew from =
the research: it works.
Get 20% off your first order with the Not Boring link [ https://substack.co=
m/redirect/995e0b1d-956c-45c5-90e3-f0de793b9573?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J=
5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,=20
Happy Monday! Hope you had a refreshing weekend; now it=E2=80=99s time to t=
alk about space factories.=20
Varda is one of the most ambitious companies I=E2=80=99ve ever come across.=
 It=E2=80=99s a space company and a biotech company rolled into one, with a=
 hypersonic testing service thrown in for good measure. Not Boring Capital =
is an investor in Varda, and I=E2=80=99ve been talking to Varda=E2=80=99s c=
o-founders, Delian and Will, about writing a piece on the company for almos=
t two years. We decided to wait until the perfect time: launch day.=20
This afternoon, Varda is going to launch a drug manufacturing factory into =
space aboard a SpaceX Falcon 9 rocket. The factory will orbit the earth for=
 a little over a month, running tests on the spacecraft and its drug manufa=
cturing capabilities, and then come hurling back down into the Utah desert =
in mid-July.=20
Because Varda does both space and bio, I teamed up with Elliot Hershberg [ =
https://substack.com/redirect/91ddf7ac-659c-454c-865f-e331fc02bcb8?j=3DeyJ1=
IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] to tell its st=
ory. In addition to being our biotech partner, Elliot writes The Century of=
 Biology . Little did he know when he started writing that the Century of B=
iology would play out both on the earth and above it. =20
I=E2=80=99ve told you that things were going to get really weird, and that =
the most interesting things were going to happen at the intersections. Vard=
a is what I=E2=80=99m talking about.=20
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.=20
Varda: The Space Drug Factory [ https://substack.com/redirect/940407e0-edfe=
-49ee-86bd-0db783ca2585?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbq=
Osa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
(Click this =F0=9F=91=86 to read the full post online)
I was on a call with Varda co-founder and CEO Will Bruey [ https://substack=
=2Ecom/redirect/2a96b5b5-6b9f-43d0-b35=
4-fb4b95fbc41a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.g=
b8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] the other day when, answering =
a question about how his company has been able to recruit so many SpaceX en=
gineers, he said something that really helped put Varda in context:=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CFor all of us who=E2=80=99ve been at SpaceX for the past decade wo=
rking on how to get up to space cheaply, once we did that, the question bec=
ame: what do we do up there? Manufacturing was the obvious next step to a l=
ot of us.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
No matter what happens next, where we currently stand in human history is m=
arvelous in the original sense of the word. Going up to space is cheap! Man=
ufacturing things in space is an obvious next step! What a time to be alive=
=2E=C2=A0
This afternoon, just 874 days into its existence, Varda [ https://substack.=
com/redirect/de34a11c-660a-4350-ba00-232c0a7de409?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb=
8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] will launch the world=E2=80=99s=
 first commercial space factory into orbit. It=E2=80=99s the company=E2=80=
=99s first test flight en route to manufacturing drugs in space for use on =
earth, and a major milestone in humanity=E2=80=99s journey to expand our ca=
pabilities beyond our home planet.
The video ends with a catchy line: =E2=80=9CGetting to space is old news. N=
ow, it=E2=80=99s what you do when you=E2=80=99re out there that counts.=E2=
=80=9D Getting to space is old news! Wild. For most of our species=E2=80=99=
 existence, getting to space was unimaginable.
For the vast, vast, vast majority of human history, everything that our anc=
estors did and made remained on earth=E2=80=99s surface and within its atmo=
sphere. A picture of earth and all of the man-made things in the sky would =
have looked like this:=C2=A0
We became a spacefaring people in 1944, when Wernher von Braun and the Nazi=
s sent the first human-made object beyond the 100 km boundary that defines =
space, the V-2 rocket.=C2=A0
It would take another thirteen years for us to send something out to space =
and get it to stay there, in orbit around the earth. In 1957, the Soviet Un=
ion launched Sputnik, the first artificial satellite to orbit the earth.=C2=
=A0
The Soviets struck again four years later, sending the first human, cosmona=
ut Yuri Gagarin, into space, where he orbited for 108 minutes on April 12, =
1961 aboard the Vostok 1. Gagarin joined a small but growing number of sate=
llites in low earth orbit (LEO), those little green dots.=C2=A0
The Soviets=E2=80=99 space supremacy spurred their Cold War rivals into act=
ion. In 1962, President John F. Kennedy =E2=80=9Cchose to go to the moon in=
 this decade [ https://substack.com/redirect/4df2facd-6c2c-4ae8-83e2-b564f3=
df4ed5?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=
,=E2=80=9D and in under seven years, NASA fulfilled his promise when Neil A=
rmstrong took =E2=80=9Cone small step for man, one giant leap for mankind.=
=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
The Americans had won the Space Race, but the Soviets continued on. In 1971=
, they launched the first space station, the Salyut 1, into orbit, marking =
the first time that humans could live and work in space for extended period=
s. They joined a growing number of LEO satellites (the green dots) and newe=
r satellites further out in geostationary orbit (GEO, the purple dots) in t=
heir journeys around the earth.=C2=A0
NASA=E2=80=99s funding plummeted after the Space Race wrapped up, but it di=
dn=E2=80=99t completely stop innovating. In 1981, the US launched the Space=
 Shuttle, the first partially reusable spacecraft. The rocket itself couldn=
=E2=80=99t be reused, but the Orbiter, the plane-looking thing strapped to =
it, carried astronauts back down to earth in relative comfort compared to s=
plash-landing in capsules.=C2=A0
The Space Shuttle would come in handy when, in 1998, construction began on =
the International Space Station, a cooperative effort between the US, Russi=
a, Japan, Europe, and Canada. Humans have continuously inhabited the ISS si=
nce its completion in 2000, where they=E2=80=99ve conducted scientific rese=
arch in microgravity spanning biology, physics, astronomy, and meteorology.=
=C2=A0
While commercial enterprises launched communications satellites, space rema=
ined largely the domain of the governments who monopolized launch capabilit=
ies until 2003, when Elon Musk founded SpaceX with the goal of building reu=
sable rockets in an effort to dramatically lower the cost of getting things=
 and people into orbit and beyond. In 2015, SpaceX successfully landed its =
Falcon 9 rocket for the first time, effectively firing the starting gun on =
the commercialization of space.=C2=A0
Just seven years after the first successful landing, the number of objects =
launched into space annually [ https://substack.com/redirect/e5614a3c-1523-=
4493-a773-ce1fccbef5f4?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqO=
sa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] has increased 10x, from 222 in 2015 to 2,163 in 2022. The =
ramp has been particularly steep since 2018, when SpaceX launched the Falco=
n Heavy, bringing launch costs down from 10x from the turn of the millennia=
, to $1,500/kg. On April 20 of this year, SpaceX launched its first orbital=
 test flight of the tallest and most powerful rocket ever flown: Starship. =
While the rocket exploded, getting that behemoth off the ground was another=
 giant leap towards a future in which launch costs on Starship reach less t=
han $100/kg.=C2=A0
We=E2=80=99ve written about it before, but it takes a lot of repetition for=
 it to sink it. We can=E2=80=99t quite grok it yet ourselves. The existence=
 of SpaceX and the dramatically cheaper and more frequent launches it offer=
s makes space businesses not only possible, but economically viable.=C2=A0
Satellites were the first step. Thousands of satellites, used primarily for=
 earth observation and communication, dot the skies. SpaceX=E2=80=99s Starl=
ink satellites make up a huge chunk of the objects in space, and their numb=
er is set to grow dramatically with Starship. In the coming years, cheap sa=
tellite internet will blanket the earth. Already, the map of 8,315 active s=
atellites [ https://substack.com/redirect/8f1061cd-bcaf-4840-b82c-44ccfe7c3=
1f5?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] or=
biting our planet looks like this:=C2=A0
But if we are to expand the economic bounds of humankind beyond our planet,=
 the economy that evolves in space will need to mirror the one that=E2=80=
=99s developed on earth.=C2=A0
Today, we=E2=80=99re entering the next frontier on that journey. At 2:19pm =
PST this afternoon, Varda is launching the world=E2=80=99s first commercial=
 space factory onboard a SpaceX rocket.=C2=A0
This first flight is mainly a test. Varda needs to prove, primarily, that i=
t can send a factory to space, orbit it around the earth, and send a capsul=
e with a payload safely back down to the planet=E2=80=99s surface.=C2=A0
If things go really well, Varda will also showcase its ability to manufactu=
re drugs in space. It will crystallize ritonavir in microgravity in order t=
o explore how gravity influences the resulting crystal structure. Ritonavir=
 is a famous example of polymorphism in pharmaceuticals, where differences =
in the symmetry and structures of the crystals lead to drastic changes in s=
olubility and bioavailability. By crystallizing pharmaceuticals in low-eart=
h orbit, Varda seeks to explore how microgravity can be used to drive novel=
 polymorphic outcomes.
It=E2=80=99s one small step on a mission to manufacture things in space for=
 use on earth as we learn to manufacture things in space for use throughout=
 the Solar System.=C2=A0
We=E2=80=99re lucky to be investors in Varda via Not Boring Capital and to =
have had an inside look at the company=E2=80=99s progress and future plans,=
 and we can=E2=80=99t think of any better time to share them than right bef=
ore the company=E2=80=99s potentially historic first launch. So today, we=
=E2=80=99ll cover:=C2=A0
The Varda Story
How to Build a Deeptech Company
Varda Goes to Washington
The Benefits of Dual Use=C2=A0
Manufacturing Drugs in Space
What to Expect from the First Mission
Expanding the Economic Bounds of Humankind
When you say the Varda concept out loud =E2=80=93 space factories making dr=
ugs in orbit =E2=80=93 it sounds crazy, or at least sci-fi, like one of tho=
se things that could maybe happen in the future but surely not now. But whe=
n you break down all of the things that go into making Varda work, from lau=
nch rideshares to satellite manufacturing to pharmaceutical research in mic=
rogravity, it all snaps into place: this is a futuristic sci-fi capability =
that=E2=80=99s both possible and practical today.=C2=A0
The Varda Story
If you=E2=80=99ve spent any time with Delian Asparouhov [ https://substack.=
com/redirect/464003e3-8108-4e4a-a71f-862261465fbd?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb=
8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], the Founders Fund partner and =
Varda co-founder, it=E2=80=99s hard to imagine him locked inside with no ou=
tlet for his energy during COVID. Delian speaks so fast his words are measu=
red in Machs. He dropped out of MIT with one course to go because they trie=
d to make him sit through a CS class on a topic he already knew. I=E2=80=99=
m surprised the photographer was able to get him to stand still for this pi=
cture.=C2=A0
So when COVID lockdowns hit, and Delian was stuck at home with the venture =
market slowing and a bunch of free time, he started re-obsessing over an id=
ea he=E2=80=99d been obsessing over for a long time: space. Specifically, D=
elian was interested in space manufacturing.=C2=A0
Space manufacturing, even manufacturing drugs in space, had made sense from=
 a technical perspective for a while. Astronauts have been doing research o=
n protein crystallization for decades, first on SkyLab in the 1970s, and on=
 the International Space Station since it went into orbit around the turn o=
f the millennium.=C2=A0
Shifting from research to manufacturing, and doing it economically and comm=
ercially, however, was still a moonshot. A company called Made in Space, fo=
unded in 2010, had seen some success building on-orbit manufacturing capabi=
lities for the ISS, but it didn=E2=80=99t reach serious scale or make much =
economic sense and was acquired by Redwire in 2020 [ https://substack.com/r=
edirect/2c9f0b7b-f6cf-4e39-9f7e-5e2e55bd3416?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7=
GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. So space manufacturing was kicked i=
nto the =E2=80=9Csci-fi things to do one day=E2=80=9D pile.=C2=A0
But by the start of COVID, the stars were starting to align, on the macro a=
nd micro levels.=C2=A0
On the macro, the ZIRP environment was fertile ground for capital intensive=
 space companies, something Delian noted on Twitter [ https://substack.com/=
redirect/9007500a-4daa-40e5-afa7-89ebe63d3cf6?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T=
7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] as he was noodling on the idea for =
Varda.=C2=A0=C2=A0
On the micro, space economics had shifted dramatically. Declining launch co=
sts could make the unit economics of space manufacturing pencil out for the=
 first time.=C2=A0
In 2019, author/astronautical engineer Robert Zubrin wrote a book called Th=
e Case for Space [ https://substack.com/redirect/7bfc5e26-5e9e-45a8-83dd-8e=
14545d2f31?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRN=
pU ]:  [ https://substack.com/redirect/7bfc5e26-5e9e-45a8-83dd-8e14545d2f31=
?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]How th=
e Revolution in Spaceflight Opens Up a Future of Limitless Possibility [ ht=
tps://substack.com/redirect/7bfc5e26-5e9e-45a8-83dd-8e14545d2f31?j=3DeyJ1Ij=
oiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. Zubrin would kn=
ow; he was partially responsible for the Revolution in Spaceflight. In 1996=
, he=E2=80=99d written The Case for Mars [ https://substack.com/redirect/1c=
b97bc9-b5cb-4330-833d-01d2230a9afe?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaM=
ZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], which inspired a young Elon Musk to start Spa=
ceX. The 2019 installment took stock of the near-term implications of that =
company=E2=80=99s impact, and the long-term possibilities as we bumped into=
 the limits of physics.=C2=A0
Zubrin goes through the math on a number of soon-economical space verticals=
, including rapid passenger travel, space tourism, space business parks, on=
-orbit research, and orbital industries. Specifically, he writes:=C2=A0
Could profitable mass-production operations actually be initiated on orbit?=
=C2=A0
The answer to this question depends upon a variety of factors, chief among =
them the cost of space launch, which today stands at roughly $5,000 per kil=
ogram to low Earth orbit. At such rates, creating orbital industries is out=
 of the question. But at the $200/kg rate that now appears to be achievable=
, matters change radically. In order for space-based manufacturing to be pr=
ofitable, the value of the goods produced per unit weight must exceed this =
figure...
Taken together, these factors would tend to rule out almost all alloy or ot=
her materials production operations, but the production of advanced compute=
r chips, unique pharmaceuticals, or lossless fiber-optic cables.=C2=A0
Reading the book helped convince Delian that the time was right to take spa=
ce manufacturing out of the =E2=80=9Csci-fi things to do one day=E2=80=9D p=
ile and make it a reality. He=E2=80=99d seen SpaceX=E2=80=99s impact firsth=
and.=C2=A0
We=E2=80=99ve shown this graph a bunch, because it=E2=80=99s the most impor=
tant one underpinning the explosion of activity in space:=C2=A0
SpaceX=E2=80=99s impact extends beyond costs, though. Elon=E2=80=99s rocket=
 company has also made getting to space more flexible and trained a new wav=
e of space talent.=C2=A0
To make space manufacturing work, Delian would need to leverage both of tho=
se opportunities. Easily bookable (and moveable) ridesharing would mean mor=
e flexibility in product development and scheduling to meet customer needs.=
 And the availability of SpaceX-trained talent =E2=80=93 a rare group that =
possessed both rocket scientist smarts and Silicon Valley speed =E2=80=93 w=
ould mean faster ramp times and a higher likelihood of success for the comp=
anies alluring enough to hire them.=C2=A0
That was the first thing Delian needed to prove to himself before starting =
the company: that he could get the right early people onboard. To be succes=
sful, the company needed to excel at three key things - manufacturing in sp=
ace, getting the payload back to Earth, and selling to both commercial and =
government customers. He=E2=80=99d need leaders who were world-class in eac=
h of the three.=C2=A0
Will Bruey [ https://substack.com/redirect/e6380564-514e-4297-bcb9-41f608bb=
6d52?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], =
Varda=E2=80=99s co-founder and CEO, is an expert at getting things back to =
earth. He spent over five years at SpaceX, where he led hardware engineerin=
g on the Dragon and was the primary mission control operator for the spacec=
raft during flight. There are very few people in the world who know reentry=
 like Will does.=C2=A0
SpaceX is one of only two private companies to successfully re-enter from o=
rbit, and when they re-enter, they do it in the Dragon capsule on which Wil=
l led hardware engineering. In March, four SpaceX astronauts splashed down =
in the Gulf of Mexico inside of a Dragon capsule. (Video of Dragon test lan=
dings [ https://substack.com/redirect/fe8800c4-55a5-47a7-86ae-8e3e05529dfc?=
j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].)=C2=
=A0
Will said that when Delian reached out, it didn=E2=80=99t take a lot of con=
vincing to get him to join on as CEO. As he mentioned in the quote at the t=
op of the piece, space manufacturing, while a wild futuristic idea to the r=
est of us, was something he and his fellow SpaceX engineers had been antici=
pating for a while. And he thought the approach that Delian laid out was th=
e right one.=C2=A0
Delian and Will incorporated Varda Space Industries, Inc. and incubated it =
out of Founders Fund. In the tradition of Founders Fund-founded aerospace a=
nd defense companies, the name Varda was plucked from the pages of J.R.R. T=
olkien=E2=80=99s The Lord of the Rings.
Palantir [ https://substack.com/redirect/d92be85f-91d0-42aa-ad94-3bc9ce38b2=
68?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], th=
e $31 billion public company that helps government clients visualize and an=
alyze data to make better decisions, is named after the book=E2=80=99s seei=
ng stones that allow their users to communicate and view events over large =
distances.=C2=A0
Anduril [ https://substack.com/redirect/84fac40f-942b-4127-8dca-c292dd1df73=
d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], the=
 $8.4 billion startup that =E2=80=9Ctransforms defense capabilities with ad=
vanced technology=E2=80=9D for western defense clients takes its name from =
the sword of Aragon whose name means =E2=80=9CFlame of the West.=E2=80=9D
The company that would bring manufacturing to space, then, would be named a=
fter Varda, the Queen of Valar [ https://substack.com/redirect/6c0e68ab-443=
2-4371-bf16-249a62f2f87f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKb=
qOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] who made the stars.
In December 2020, the newly formed Varda raised a $9 million Seed round co-=
led by Founders Fund and Lux Capital.=C2=A0
Varda now had the money and the expertise to send things from the heavens b=
ack down to earth, but they still needed to figure out how to make things u=
p there.
When he was considering joining Varda, Will called his Cornell classmate, A=
drian Radocea [ https://substack.com/redirect/45a9c67d-cd43-425a-b2fb-75e14=
9670742?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU =
], a materials science PhD who=E2=80=99d been working on materials for semi=
conductors, to ask a crucial question: =E2=80=9CDoes microgravity matter fo=
r materials?=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Adrian was dismissive: =E2=80=9CAbsolutely not,=E2=80=9D he told Will. =E2=
=80=9CAt the atomic scale, the force of gravity is nothing compared to the =
electrostatic force.=E2=80=9D (The electrostatic force between a proton and=
 electron is 1036 more powerful than the gravitational force.)=C2=A0
But it was COVID, and Adrian was stuck at home, too. So he started reading =
scientific articles on the question and came across literature on the effec=
t of microgravity on protein crystallization. Turns out, microgravity does =
matter at the mesoscopic scale, =E2=80=8B=E2=80=8Bthe length scale on which=
 objects are larger than nanoscale (on the order of atoms and molecules) bu=
t still small enough that quantum mechanical or other non-trivial "microsco=
pic" behavior becomes apparent. This is the scale at which protein crystall=
ization occurs, which has important implications for pharmaceutical manufac=
turing.=C2=A0
He called Will back to tell him that there might actually be something ther=
e, and that he wanted to come help figure it out. Adrian joined Varda as th=
e Head of Product.=C2=A0
Now the only questions left were what exactly to make and who would be will=
ing to buy it.=C2=A0
So Delian and Will tapped Eric Lasker [ https://substack.com/redirect/3ee22=
867-6526-472c-a420-3fa045fdbb8a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjm=
lXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], a physicist by education who worked as a cook at=
 Michelin Star restaurants before transitioning to the business side of sta=
rtups. Eric worked in Enterprise Sales and Market Development at Stripe and=
 then led US Federal Partnerships for Zipline [ https://substack.com/redire=
ct/c0d278e3-be27-486f-93e7-c8dc042cfd52?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Z=
lNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], the autonomous drone delivery company.=
=C2=A0
They gave him his task: =E2=80=9CGo build a business.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
They knew that they=E2=80=99d be able to launch factories into space, make =
things up there, and send them back down, and they had ideas about the type=
s of things you could make up there and that a rare commercial reentry vehi=
cle that didn=E2=80=99t have human cargo might be valuable to the DoD, but =
that was about it. There were no comps for a business like Varda.=C2=A0
January 19, 2021 was Day 1 at Varda. Will, Delian, Adrian, Eric, COO Jon Ba=
rr, and a handful of aerospace engineers got to work.=C2=A0
The engineers, many of whom Will had brought over from SpaceX, knew where t=
o start. They=E2=80=99d need to figure out how to build their satellite fac=
tory and capsule.=C2=A0
Meanwhile, Eric and Adrian started figuring out which markets to attack fir=
st, and who would be willing to pay them for their out of this world capabi=
lities, and quickly.
The Varda story can=E2=80=99t be contained to this planet=E2=80=A6 or to th=
e email length limit. To learn about how to build a deeptech company, reent=
ry-as-a-service, the benefits of being dual-use, why pharma wants to manufa=
cture drugs in space, what to expect from today=E2=80=99s launch, and where=
 Varda is heading=E2=80=A6=20
Thanks to Elliot [ https://substack.com/redirect/91ddf7ac-659c-454c-865f-e3=
31fc02bcb8?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRN=
pU ] for writing this with me, to Delian, Will, Eric, Adrian, and the Varda=
 team for helping us get up to speed, and to Dan [ https://substack.com/red=
irect/a80bf9de-9ae3-4152-ad19-84dc5decc791?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7Gn=
A_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] for editing.
That=E2=80=99s all for today. We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox on Friday=
 for the Weekly Dose and we=E2=80=99ll be back on the summer schedule next =
Tuesday.
Thanks for reading,
Packy

